      "id": 1,
      "text": "Aurora began as the village of Scipio, was renamed Aurora in 1795, and officially incorporated under that name in 1837.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://auroranewyork.us/about/history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Founded in 1804, Aurora grew into a bustling community before officially becoming a village in 1874.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Aurora%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1868, Henry Wells opened Wells College for women, a pioneering institution in the region.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://auroranewyork.us/about/history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Roycroft Inn, once a print shop, welcomed travelers as an inn in 1905, showcasing Mission‑style furniture.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Aurora%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "In 1986, the Roycroft Campus earned National Landmark status, preserving its legacy of artisan craftsmanship.",
